### RESEARCHER-B Round 1

Summary of this research round: The FDA has not created a special “fast lane” for molecules merely because they were designed with AI; its public outputs from 2024–2026 instead build a risk‑based credibility framework for AI models used to support regulatory decisions, and the draft guidance explicitly says it does not cover the use of AI in drug discovery (see the FDA guidance page: https://www.fda.gov/regulatory-information/search-fda-guidance-documents/considerations-use-artificial-intelligence-support-regulatory-decision-making-drug-and-biological and the draft guidance text: https://www.fda.gov/media/184830/download). Separately, programs like the FDA’s ISTAND pilot are qualifying AI/digital tools that can improve measurements or endpoints (which could indirectly speed certain trials) but do not create an expedited approval pathway for AI‑origin compounds (ISTAND press: https://www.fda.gov/drugs/drug-safety-and-availability/fdas-istand-pilot-program-accepts-submission-first-artificial-intelligence-based-and-digital-health). Practical implication for a 6–12 month (to Sept 2026) retail-investor horizon: AI may materially shorten early discovery timelines, but regulatory approval timing will continue to be driven by clinical evidence and credibility of data submitted, so expect limited regulatory upside purely from “AI-designed” status within your window. (yellow)

